    <text>
        <front>
            <div type="summary">
                <p>
                    ABOUT FUTURE MARKETING STRATEGIES 
                </p>
            </div>
        </front>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName>
                            London
                        </placeName>
                        <date when="YYYY-MM-DD">
                            31st January 1931
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>
                           <persName>Leonard Woolf,Esq.</persName> 
                           <orgName>The Hogarth Press</orgName>
                        </addrLine>
                        <addrLine>
                            52,Tavistock Square <lb/> W.C.I.
                        </addrLine>
                    </address>
                    <salute>
                        Dear Mr.Woolf
                    </salute>
                </opener>

                <p>
                    The trouble about the rise of 15% lies in the <lb/>
                    figures of American production costs, which are of course, higher <lb/>
                    than over here, and in the fact that the American bookseller has <lb/>
                    established a claim to a higher percentage reduction from the <lb/>
                    publisher than he receives over here. We can make a profit on<lb/>
                    15%, but only if we are able to have a run of something like<lb/>
                    10,000 copies at the beginning - that is to say, if the author's<lb/>
                    market is established. If we have to print in driblets, 15%<lb/>
                    to the author just wipes out our profit. Ten per cent we <lb/>
                    can do. Now, Hampson may be a great success, but at the best <lb/>
                    he is an experiment. I don't know exactly what shall print,<lb/>
                    but I am sure it will have to be small. <lb/>

                </p>

                <p>
                    Some day , hempson, I hope will be a big <lb/>
                    seller. but if this is to be so, it will have to be partly<lb/>
                    our doing. It is really to his interest to let us have a <lb/>
                    chance and not press too hard at the beginning.
                </p>

                <closer>
                <persNname>R.W.Postgate,European Representative</persNname>
                <orgName>ALFRED A.KNOPF,Inc <lb/>New York</orgName>
                <address>
                    4 Elm Close<lb/>London N W 4
                </address>
                    <salute>
                        Yours sincerely,
                    </salute>
                    <signed/>
                   
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
